<subSubSection id="65C4E3E5C46AFFC5FF205E8FBAEAFC6D" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="2D61B06EC46AFFC5FF205E8FB8A3FD02" blockId="13.[151,394,712,739]" box="[151,394,712,739]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">
<heading id="76290702C46AFFC5FF205E8FB8A3FD02" bold="true" box="[151,394,712,739]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" reason="1">
<taxonomicName id="EADECBEDC46AFFC5FF205E8FB8A3FD02" authority="Hinds" authorityName="Hinds" box="[151,394,712,739]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Malacothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1FAA6C7CC46AFFC5FF205E8FB8A3FD02" bold="true" box="[151,394,712,739]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">
<emphasis id="1FAA6C7CC46AFFC5FF205E8FB811FD03" bold="true" box="[151,312,713,739]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">Malacothrips</emphasis>
Hinds
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2D61B06EC46AFFC5FF205F4FBAEAFC6D" blockId="13.[151,1436,777,1161]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">
Worldwide there are 
<number id="9B16A249C46AFFC5FE335F4FB889FCC1" box="[388,416,777,801]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" value="15.0">15</number>
species listed in this genus, but these are possibly not all closely related. Five of them are from Africa, but even the nine New World species in the key provided by 
<bibRefCitation id="494FCD9FC46AFFC5FC7B5F6BBC29FCA5" author="Mound" box="[972,1280,813,837]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Marullo, R. (1996) The Thrips of Central and South America: An Introduction. Memoirs on Entomology, International, 6, 1 - 488." type="journal article" year="1996">
Mound and Marullo (
<number id="9B16A249C46AFFC5FB0C5F6BBDDEFCA5" box="[1211,1271,813,837]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" value="1996.0">1996</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, are curiously diverse. No species of 
<taxonomicName id="EADECBEDC46AFFC5FE2D5F17BB18FC89" box="[410,561,849,873]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Malacothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1FAA6C7CC46AFFC5FE2D5F17BB18FC89" box="[410,561,849,873]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">Malacothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has yet been recorded from 
<collectingCountry id="55C9F0FEC46AFFC5FCC05F17BAC8FC89" box="[887,993,849,873]" name="Australia" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">Australia</collectingCountry>
, but two specimens in 
<collectionCode id="4BCF28ABC46AFFC5FB505F17BC06FC89" LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:32981" box="[1255,1327,849,873]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:32981" name="Australian National Insect Collection" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">ANIC</collectionCode>
, from the Northern Territory near Darwin, appear to represent this genus (
<figureCitation id="B5E5ACEBC46AFFC5FCD55F33BA9FFC6D" box="[866,950,885,909]" captionStart="FIGURES 26 – 31" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1949,1972]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,409,1928]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,409,1928]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 26 – 31. Phlaeothripinae genera. (26) Jacotia glyptus; (27) Macrophthalmothrips argus; (28) Majerthrips barrowi; (29) Malacothrips sp.; (30) Mystrothrips sp.; (31) Octurothrips pulcher." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/247296/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">
Fig. 
<number id="9B16A249C46AFFC5FC215F33BA9FFC6D" box="[918,950,885,909]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" value="29.0">29</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="65C4E3E5C46AFFC5FF705FDFB8E8FB69" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="2D61B06EC46AFFC5FF705FDFB8E8FB69" blockId="13.[151,1436,777,1161]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">
<emphasis id="1FAA6C7CC46AFFC5FF705FDFB868FC52" bold="true" box="[199,321,921,946]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Head longer than wide, cheeks with weak setae; postocular setae long, capitate; stylets usually about one fifth of head width apart; antennae 
<number id="9B16A249C46AFFC5FD115FFBBB9BFC35" box="[678,690,957,981]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" value="8.0">8</number>
-segmented, VIII with basal neck, III with 
<number id="9B16A249C46AFFC5FB165FFBBD86FC35" box="[1185,1199,957,981]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" value="3.0">3</number>
sensoria, IV with 
<number id="9B16A249C46AFFC5FA315FFBBCBEFC35" box="[1414,1431,957,981]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" value="4.0">4</number>
; pronotum usually with 
<number id="9B16A249C46AFFC5FE145FA7B898FC19" box="[419,433,993,1017]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" value="4.0">4</number>
pairs of slender, capitate setae, anteromarginals reduced; notopleural sutures complete; basantra present; mesopraesternum variable; sternopleural sutures present; fore tarsi usually with tooth in both sexes; fore wings weakly constricted medially, with or without duplicated cilia; pelta bell-shaped; tergites II–VII each with 
<number id="9B16A249C46AFFC5FEB9580BB835FB85" box="[270,284,1101,1125]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" value="2.0">2</number>
pairs of wing retaining setae; tube shorter than head, anal setae longer than tube; male sternite VIII with or without pore plate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
